questionBank.computer.set3.push(
    { q: "In CIDR notation, if a network is defined as /28, mathematically how many usable host IP addresses does it provide?", options: ["254", "128", "30", "14"], ans: 3, exp: "A /28 mathematically leaves 4 bits for hosts. 2^4 = 16. Subtract 2 (for Network and Broadcast addresses) = exactly 14 usable hosts." },
    { q: "What is the primary technical advantage of the 'WireGuard' VPN protocol over older protocols like OpenVPN or IPsec?", options: ["It is older and more extensively tested", "It utilizes a significantly smaller, mathematically streamlined codebase (approx 4,000 lines), resulting in vastly faster connection times and less CPU overhead", "It does not use encryption mathematically", "It only works on Linux OS"], ans: 1, exp: "WireGuard's mathematically small codebase makes it exceptionally fast and incredibly easy to audit for security flaws." },
    { q: "In DNS architecture, what does an 'A Record' mathematically do?", options: ["Provides an alias for a completely different domain", "Maps a human-readable domain name (like example.com) directly to a 32-bit IPv4 address mathematically", "Secures the website with SSL encryption", "Routes email traffic mathematically to a server"], ans: 1, exp: "The 'A' (Address) record is the most fundamental DNS entry, directing your browser to the physical server." },
    { q: "What does 'Port Address Translation' (PAT), commonly referred to as NAT Overload, achieve?", options: ["Translates web pages to different languages", "A mathematical feature allowing thousands of internal local devices to share a single public IP address by assigning a unique, temporary port number to every single outbound request", "Blocks all ports mathematically", "Encrypts the router connection"], ans: 1, exp: "When Google replies, the router mathematically looks at the specific port number to know exactly which local laptop requested that data." },
    { q: "Which port number is universally standard for the secure, encrypted Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP)?", options: ["Port 22", "Port 80", "Port 443", "Port 3389"], ans: 3, exp: "Leaving Port 3389 mathematically exposed to the open internet is a massive security risk frequently exploited by ransomware gangs." },
    { q: "In the OSI model, which specific layer is responsible for hardware MAC addressing?", options: ["Layer 1 (Physical)", "Layer 2 (Data Link)", "Layer 3 (Network)", "Layer 4 (Transport)"], ans: 1, exp: "Network switches operate mathematically at Layer 2, moving frames locally using hardcoded 48-bit MAC addresses." },
    { q: "What does 'SNMP' strictly stand for in network management?", options: ["Secure Network Mail Protocol", "Simple Network Management Protocol", "System Node Mapping Process", "Synchronous Network Media Port"], ans: 1, exp: "SNMP is the universal protocol mathematically used to monitor, manage, and configure devices (like routers, switches, and servers) on an IP network." },
    { q: "In Wi-Fi security, what does 'WPA3' mathematically represent?", options: ["A type of physical Ethernet cable", "A dynamic routing protocol", "The latest and most mathematically secure Wi-Fi encryption standard", "A high-speed web browser"], ans: 2, exp: "Wi-Fi Protected Access 3 (WPA3) provides individualized mathematical data encryption to protect against offline password guessing." },
    { q: "What does 'BGP' (Border Gateway Protocol) mathematically execute?", options: ["Provides local Wi-Fi passwords", "Mathematically determines the most efficient routing paths across the massive, interconnected Autonomous Systems that make up the global internet", "Blocks viruses at the firewall", "Assigns local MAC addresses"], ans: 1, exp: "If a major submarine cable is severed, BGP mathematically recalculates the global map and reroutes internet traffic around the outage." },
    { q: "What is an 'ARP Spoofing' (ARP Poisoning) attack?", options: ["Deleting the router's operating system", "A Man-in-the-Middle attack where a hacker sends mathematically falsified ARP messages over a LAN to link their own MAC address with the IP address of the legitimate default gateway", "Guessing a Wi-Fi password mathematically", "A DDoS attack on a web server"], ans: 1, exp: "Once poisoned, all network traffic mathematically intended for the internet routes directly through the hacker's laptop instead of the real router." },
    { q: "What is the exact physical length of an IPv6 address?", options: ["32 bits", "64 bits", "128 bits", "256 bits"], ans: 2, exp: "IPv6 consists of 128 bits, mathematically providing 3.4 x 10^38 unique addresses, typically written in hexadecimal format." },
    { q: "What does the networking command 'ping' actually execute?", options: ["It resets the router mathematically", "It sends an ICMP Echo Request packet to a target host and precisely measures the mathematical round-trip time in milliseconds", "It downloads a massive test file", "It changes the DNS server address"], ans: 1, exp: "Ping is the most fundamental diagnostic mathematical tool for testing network connectivity and latency." },
    { q: "What is a 'VLAN' (Virtual Local Area Network)?", options: ["A completely wireless router", "A mathematical configuration on a network switch that logically groups specific devices into an isolated broadcast domain, regardless of their physical location", "A cloud server environment", "A VPN connection"], ans: 1, exp: "VLANs mathematically improve security and reduce broadcast congestion by completely isolating traffic (e.g., keeping guest Wi-Fi separate from the HR department)." },
    { q: "What does the 'HTTPS' protocol mathematically utilize to secure web traffic?", options: ["MAC address filtering", "SSL/TLS cryptographic certificates", "Subnet masking", "HTML code encryption"], ans: 1, exp: "Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) and Transport Layer Security (TLS) mathematically scramble data so interceptors cannot read it." },
    { q: "What is the primary mathematical difference between TCP and UDP protocols?", options: ["UDP is encrypted, TCP is completely plain-text", "TCP mathematically guarantees data delivery and order; UDP sends data continuously without verifying receipt, making it faster but less reliable", "TCP is for wireless, UDP is for wired", "There is no mathematical difference"], ans: 1, exp: "TCP is used for downloading files (where every byte mathematically matters). UDP is used for live video (where a dropped frame is ignored)." }
);

// --- COMPUTER: SET 4 (Storage & Memory) ---
questionBank.computer.set4.push(
    { q: "What is the strict mathematical minimum number of hard drives required to build a RAID 5 array?", options: ["2 drives", "3 drives", "4 drives", "5 drives"], ans: 1, exp: "RAID 5 requires a minimum of 3 drives to implement block-level striping with mathematically distributed parity across all disks." },
    { q: "In enterprise virtualization (like VMware), what is the exact mathematical difference between 'Thick Provisioning' and 'Thin Provisioning' of storage?", options: ["There is no mathematical difference", "Thick provisioning instantly reserves the entire allocated physical disk space upfront (e.g., 500GB); Thin provisioning mathematically allocates physical space only as data is actually written to the virtual drive", "Thick provisioning is for cloud only", "Thin provisioning compresses data mathematically"], ans: 1, exp: "Thin provisioning mathematically saves immense money but runs the risk of crashing if the physical storage pool actually runs out of space." },
    { q: "What does 'RAID 0' accomplish?", options: ["Absolute mathematical data safety", "It mathematically splits (stripes) data across multiple drives to drastically improve read/write speeds, but offers exactly zero redundancy", "It encrypts data entirely", "It compresses data by 50%"], ans: 1, exp: "Because data is mathematically split, if one drive in a RAID 0 array dies, all data across all drives is permanently lost." },
    { q: "What is the primary architectural difference between a SAN (Storage Area Network) and a NAS (Network Attached Storage)?", options: ["SANs are completely wireless", "SAN provides mathematically raw, block-level access to storage, appearing to servers exactly as local internal drives; NAS provides file-level access with built-in folder structures", "SAN is slower than NAS", "There is no functional difference"], ans: 1, exp: "Enterprise databases mathematically require the high-speed, raw block access of a SAN. Office workers sharing Word documents use a NAS." },
    { q: "What does the 'NVMe' protocol explicitly utilize to achieve massive data transfer speeds?", options: ["The legacy SATA III interface", "The high-bandwidth PCIe (Peripheral Component Interconnect Express) lanes, bypassing older, slower storage controllers completely", "USB 3.0 ports", "The motherboard RAM slots"], ans: 1, exp: "By connecting directly to the PCIe bus, NVMe SSDs reduce latency and increase throughput astronomically compared to SATA HDDs." },
    { q: "What does 'EEPROM' stand for?", options: ["External Execution Protocol Read-Only Memory", "Electrically Erasable Programmable Read-Only Memory", "Encrypted Electronic Processor ROM", "Enhanced Energy Portable ROM"], ans: 1, exp: "EEPROM allows precise individual bytes of memory to be erased and rewritten mathematically via electrical currents, forming the foundation of modern Flash memory." },
    { q: "What is 'Defragmentation' on a mechanical hard drive?", options: ["Deleting personal files securely", "The process of mathematically consolidating scattered, fragmented files into contiguous blocks on the magnetic platter to improve mechanical read/write speeds", "Erasing the drive for resale", "Creating a mathematically exact backup copy"], ans: 1, exp: "Defragmentation prevents the mechanical read/write head from having to jump all over the platter to mathematically read a single file." },
    { q: "What does the 'TRIM' command specifically do in SSD management?", options: ["It compresses large files mathematically", "It actively informs the SSD controller which data blocks are no longer needed, allowing the drive to wipe them internally in advance and maintain high mathematical write speeds", "It encrypts the SSD entirely", "It checks for viruses"], ans: 1, exp: "Without TRIM, SSDs suffer severe performance drops because they must mathematically erase blocks simultaneously while trying to write new data." },
    { q: "What is 'Wear Leveling' on a Solid State Drive?", options: ["A physical shock absorber casing", "An internal controller algorithm that mathematically distributes write/erase cycles evenly across all NAND flash memory blocks to prevent individual blocks from dying prematurely", "A cooling heatsink", "A file deletion tool"], ans: 1, exp: "Flash memory has a mathematically finite number of write cycles. Wear leveling ensures the entire drive ages uniformly." },
    { q: "Exactly how many Gigabytes (GB) are mathematically contained in one Terabyte (TB) using traditional binary prefixes?", options: ["1000", "1024", "1048", "2048"], ans: 1, exp: "Because computer architecture is based entirely on binary (base-2), storage scales precisely by powers of 2. 2^10 = 1024." },
    { q: "Which file system was specifically designed by Apple to optimize flash/SSD storage on macOS?", options: ["NTFS", "FAT32", "ext4", "APFS (Apple File System)"], ans: 3, exp: "APFS features strong native encryption, space sharing, and mathematically instantaneous file cloning." },
    { q: "What is 'LTO' (Linear Tape-Open) primarily used for?", options: ["High-speed PC gaming", "Booting the operating system mathematically", "Massive, highly durable, offline archival data backups", "Connecting to Wi-Fi networks"], ans: 2, exp: "LTO magnetic tape is incredibly cheap per terabyte and can store data safely for up to 30 years." },
    { q: "What does 'S.M.A.R.T.' status monitoring do on a hard drive?", options: ["It formats the drive automatically", "Self-Monitoring, Analysis, and Reporting Technology constantly measures internal physical parameters (like bad sectors) to mathematically predict an impending hardware failure", "It encrypts stored data mathematically", "It boosts the RPM of the drive"], ans: 1, exp: "A S.M.A.R.T. warning is a critical mathematical indicator that you must back up your data immediately." },
    { q: "What is 'Deduplication' in enterprise backup environments?", options: ["Copying a file twice for safety mathematically", "A mathematical process that identifies and eliminates redundant data blocks, storing only one unique instance and replacing all other duplicates with tiny mathematical reference pointers", "Compressing files into a ZIP format", "Deleting files older than 30 days"], ans: 1, exp: "Deduplication drastically reduces storage requirements. If 1,000 employees have the same Windows update file, it is mathematically only stored on the server once." },
    { q: "What does it mathematically mean when storage is 'Volatile'?", options: ["It is prone to catching fire", "It requires continuous electrical power to mathematically retain its state; if power is lost, the data is instantly and completely erased", "It cannot be physically erased", "It is used exclusively for the BIOS"], ans: 1, exp: "RAM and CPU Cache are mathematically volatile. HDDs and SSDs are non-volatile." }
);

